"title": "7540: Judaism",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "7540",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Derived from “Judah” (the southern kingdom of the divided monarchy) the term refers to the religion and culture of the Jews from the time of the exile (586 B.C.) onwards.</p>\n<h2>The exile and the beginnings of Judaism</h2>\n<h3>The people of Judah become known as Jews</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra4:12\">EZR 4:12</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Neh4:2\">NEH 4:2</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Esth3:6\">EST 3:6</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer32:12\">JER 32:12</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt2:2\">MAT 2:2</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John2:6\">JHN 2:6</a></p>\n<h3>Jewish communities were formed in many places</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer44:1\">JER 44:1</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra2:1\">EZR 2:1</a> <em>many stayed in Babylon</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John7:35\">JHN 7:35</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts2:8-Acts2:11\">ACT 2:8–2:11</a></p>\n<h3>Far from the Jerusalem temple, the exiles had difficulty in knowing how to worship</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps137:4\">PSA 137:4</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos3:4\">HOS 3:4</a> <em>This prophecy to Israel also expresses the dilemma of the Jerusalem exiles.</em></p>\n<h2>New forms of religion after the exile, probably beginning in Babylon</h2>\n<h3>Emphasis on the Scriptures</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Neh7:73-Neh8:3\">NEH 7:73–8:3</a></p>\n<h3>Synagogue worship</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke4:16-Luke4:17\">LUK 4:16–4:17</a> <em>Unable to sacrifice in the temple, the exiles would have focused their worship on the Scriptures, a practice which developed into synagogue worship.</em></p>\n<h3>Carefully observing the law</h3>\n<p>Ezra went from Babylon to Jerusalem with the express intention of seeing that God's law was observed:\n <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra7:11\">EZR 7:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra7:14\">EZR 7:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra7:25\">EZR 7:25</a></p>\n<h2>The temple and sacrifice</h2>\n<h3>The returning exiles recommence the sacrifices</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra3:1-Ezra3:6\">EZR 3:1–3:6</a></p>\n<h3>The temple rebuilt</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra3:8\">EZR 3:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra6:14-Ezra6:15\">EZR 6:14–6:15</a></p>\n<h3>The temple as a focus for pilgrims</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John12:20\">JHN 12:20</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts2:5\">ACT 2:5</a> <em>They had probably come for Passover and were staying until Pentecost</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts8:27\">ACT 8:27</a></p>\n<h3>The temple regarded with great reverence</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt26:59-Matt26:61\">MAT 26:59–26:61</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:57-Mark14:58\">MRK 14:57–14:58</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts6:13\">ACT 6:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts21:27-Acts21:29\">ACT 21:27–21:29</a></p>\n<h2>Studying and obeying the law</h2>\n<h3>Studying Scripture</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John5:39\">JHN 5:39</a></p>\n<h3>Total obedience essential</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt23:23\">MAT 23:23</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jas2:10\">JAS 2:10</a></p>\n<h3>Human rules added to God's law</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt23:16-Matt23:18\">MAT 23:16–23:18</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark7:1-Mark7:13\">MRK 7:1–7:13</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt15:1-Matt15:9\">MAT 15:1–15:9</a></p>\n<h3>High regard for the Sabbath and traditional rules associated with it</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt12:1-Matt12:2\">MAT 12:1–12:2</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark2:23-Mark2:24\">MRK 2:23–2:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke6:1-Luke6:2\">LUK 6:1–6:2</a></p>\n<h2>Groups within NT Judaism</h2>\n<h3>Pharisees</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark7:3-Mark7:4\">MRK 7:3–7:4</a></strong> <em>The Pharisees stressed the fulfilment of the law by individuals.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke11:38\">LUK 11:38</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke18:10-Luke18:12\">LUK 18:10–18:12</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts26:5\">ACT 26:5</a></p>\n<h3>Sadducees</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts5:17\">ACT 5:17</a></strong> <em>A powerful minority group, politically astute whilst theologically conservative, they saw temple worship as the chief purpose of the law.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt3:7\">MAT 3:7</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark12:18\">MRK 12:18</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt22:23\">MAT 22:23</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke20:27\">LUK 20:27</a></p>\n<h3>Teachers of the law (scribes)</h3>\n<p>They preserved, copied, taught and administered the law:\n <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt17:10\">MAT 17:10</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark9:14\">MRK 9:14</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke2:46\">LUK 2:46</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts4:5\">ACT 4:5</a></p>\n<h3>Zealots</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke6:15\">LUK 6:15</a> <em>They favoured a “holy war” to drive out the Romans.</em></p>\n<h3>Non-Jewish converts</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt23:15\">MAT 23:15</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts2:11\">ACT 2:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts6:5\">ACT 6:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts13:43\">ACT 13:43</a></p>\n<h2>Judaism and Christianity</h2>\n<h3>Conflict between Jesus Christ and the Jewish authorities</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:1\">MRK 14:1</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John11:45-John11:50\">JHN 11:45–11:50</a></p>\n<h3>Conflict between the first Christians and Judaism</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John16:2\">JHN 16:2</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts4:1-Acts4:3\">ACT 4:1–4:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts5:17-Acts5:18\">ACT 5:17–5:18</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal1:13-Gal1:14\">GAL 1:13–1:14</a></p>\n<h3>Conflict produced by Jewish influence among the first Christians</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts15:5\">ACT 15:5</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts15:1-Acts15:2\">ACT 15:1–15:2</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal2:11-Gal2:16\">GAL 2:11–2:16</a> <em>Judaism gave birth to Christianity. After an initial uneasy co-existence a total break finally ensued.</em></p>",
